Do I Need to Build a Brand?

*Bounce, swoosh.*

What image comes to mind?

I’ll bet within a few guesses you would think of the world famous NIKE logo.

*A polar bear wearing a red scarf.* 

*A blue oval car emblem.* 

*One bite out of an…*

I don’t even need to finish the sentence. Likely, you very quickly recognize the brand names represented by each of these descriptions.

This is branding at its best. NIKE, Coca-Cola, Ford, and Apple have so well branded their companies that their logos are recognizable nearly anywhere in the world.

Successful branding is simply a matter of stamping your name and logo any place where the most people will see it.

Branding is all about creating familiarity. Coke wants everyone to be familiar with their brand, whether it’s John Doe or Warren Buffet. Since people are subconsciously biased towards whatever they are most familiar with, a company like Coca-Cola seeks to create familiarity with their brand.

**Branding** is about becoming a recognized company among a population. While large corporations seek to establish a national or global brand, small or niche businesses may choose to establish their brand within a specific geography or demographic.

**Direct response** marketing, on the other hand, seeks to create calls-to-action to a specific audience in a way that you can measure effectiveness. It’s a specific aim at a target audience with the goal of measuring your return.

Branding and direct response are not mutually exclusive. Because branding increases visibility, it can actually serve to *increase* the effectiveness of a targeted advertisement campaign. For example, a  B2B company may choose to develop a branding campaign to gain general visibility among businesses matching their client profile (hoping to increase the likelihood of a sale). However, their advertisements will target specific business people (perhaps leads or targeted prospects) with a particular call-to-action which they can measure. 

As a business owner, discern who and where your customer base is. When creating your advertisements, determine your goal: are you simply looking to build awareness or are you looking for a specific action from your customers?

Understanding this will help you know how to best get your customer’s attention, and whether to use an online or offline medium. It will also help you know exactly how to craft your advertisements and how to target your specific demographic. In addition, you will be able to measure the effectiveness of your direct response marketing, giving you specific data on how to improve your advertising strategies.

Sometimes business owners get caught in the trap of focusing only on branding or only on direct response, but skillfully combining both in your marketing will give you a competitive edge in reaching your customers.
